# Angular Development Guidelines

## Project Structure

- Follow a feature-based organization for modules and components
- Use the following folder structure:
  ```
  libs/
    feature-name/
      feature/
        src/
          lib/
            components/
            services/
            models/
            utils/
  ```
- Keep related files close to each other
- Use barrel files (index.ts) to simplify imports

## Component Guidelines

- Use OnPush change detection strategy for better performance
- Keep components small and focused on a single responsibility
- Extract reusable UI elements into separate components
- Use smart/dumb component pattern (container/presentational)
- Avoid logic in templates; move complex logic to the component class or services
- Use trackBy with ngFor for better performance

## Naming Conventions

- Use kebab-case for file names: `feature-name.component.ts`
- Use PascalCase for class names: `FeatureNameComponent`
- Use camelCase for properties and methods
- Add the type in the file name: `.component.ts`, `.service.ts`, `.pipe.ts`
- Use descriptive, clear names that explain the purpose

## TypeScript Best Practices

- Use strict mode and strict type checking
- Define interfaces for all data structures
- Use readonly for immutable properties
- Avoid any type when possible
- Use access modifiers (private, protected, public) appropriately
- Use const for variables that don't change

## State Management

- Use services with RxJS for simple state management
- Consider NgRx for complex applications with many state transitions
- Keep state normalized and avoid duplication
- Use the async pipe in templates to subscribe to observables
- Properly manage subscriptions (use takeUntil, async pipe, or subscription management)

## Performance Optimization

- Use OnPush change detection
- Lazy load feature modules
- Implement virtual scrolling for long lists
- Use pure pipes instead of methods in templates
- Optimize images and assets
- Use web workers for CPU-intensive tasks

## Testing

- Write unit tests for all components and services
- Use TestBed for Angular-specific testing
- Mock dependencies appropriately
- Test edge cases and error scenarios
- Aim for high test coverage

## Tailwind CSS Guidelines

- Use Tailwind utility classes directly in templates instead of custom CSS/SCSS
- Follow mobile-first responsive design approach using Tailwind's responsive prefixes (sm:, md:, lg:, etc.)
- Group related utility classes in a logical order (layout → sizing → spacing → typography → colors → effects)
- Extract common patterns to Tailwind components using the @layer components directive when needed
- Use Tailwind's JIT mode for optimal performance and bundle size
- Leverage Tailwind's theme customization in tailwind.config.js for brand colors and design tokens
- Avoid mixing custom CSS with Tailwind unless absolutely necessary
- Use arbitrary values (e.g., w-[327px]) sparingly and prefer the predefined scale
- For complex components, consider using Tailwind's @apply directive in a separate CSS file
- Keep accessibility in mind when choosing colors (ensure sufficient contrast)

## Accessibility

- Follow WCAG 2.1 guidelines
- Use semantic HTML elements
- Include proper ARIA attributes
- Ensure keyboard navigation works
- Test with screen readers

## Error Handling

- Implement global error handling
- Use try/catch blocks for error-prone code
- Display user-friendly error messages
- Log errors for debugging
- Handle HTTP errors consistently

## Security

- Sanitize user inputs
- Protect against XSS attacks
- Implement proper authentication and authorization
- Use HttpInterceptors for adding auth tokens
- Follow Angular security best practices

## Code Quality

- Use ESLint and Prettier for code formatting and linting
- Follow the Angular style guide
- Conduct regular code reviews
- Refactor code when necessary
- Document complex logic with comments

## Build and Deployment

- Use environment-specific configuration
- Optimize bundles for production
- Implement CI/CD pipelines
- Use semantic versioning
- Create comprehensive documentation

## Angular Material Usage

- Follow Material Design principles
- Use Angular Material components consistently
- Customize the theme to match brand guidelines
- Extend components rather than modifying them
- Use CDK for custom components when needed
- Apply Tailwind classes to Material components for custom styling when needed

## RxJS Best Practices

- Use appropriate operators
- Avoid nested subscriptions
- Handle errors in observables
- Complete observables to prevent memory leaks
- Use higher-order mapping operators (switchMap, mergeMap, etc.) appropriately

## Internationalization (i18n)

- Use Angular's i18n system or ngx-translate
- Externalize all user-facing strings
- Support right-to-left languages
- Format dates, numbers, and currencies according to locale
- Test with different languages and locales
